widgets_values:
This node is to avoid bad output results caused by excessively large input image sizes. Because when we input one image, we use the size of that input image.

The **TextEncodeQwenImageEditPlus** will scale your input to 1024×104 pixels. We use the size of your first input image. This node is to avoid having an input image size that is too large (such as 3000×3000 pixels), which could bring bad results.

Move the camera to a back-facing position so the full body of the character is visible. The character stands with both arms extended slightly downward and close to the thighs, keeping the body evenly balanced on both sides. Background is plain white.

nodes.title: Note: About image size
widgets_values: You can use the latent from the **EmptySD3LatentImage** to replace **VAE Encode**, so you can customize the image size.

nodes.title: Note: KSampler settings
widgets_values:
You can test and find the best setting by yourself. The following table is for reference.

| Model            | Steps | CFG |
|---------------------|---------------|---------------|
| Offical             | 50               | 4.0               
| fp8_e4m3fn             | 20                | 2.5               |
| fp8_e4m3fn + 4steps LoRA    | 4               | 1.0               |

Move the camera to a front-facing position so the full body of the character is visible. The character stands with both arms extended slightly downward and close to the thighs, keeping the body evenly balanced on both sides. Background is plain white.

nodes.title: Character Image & Other Notes
widgets_values:
This workflow is pretty automatic. It either works or it doesn't. You can adjust minor details though.

Put an image of a character, preferably forward-facing, entirely in view, unobscurred, but Qwen Edit does a good job guessing hidden details.

Does all styles pretty well, props and scenes are ignored.

The 'character image padding' above 'Image Trim & Concat Group' determines the amount of white pixels that surrounds each character direction. The default of 40 is fine for most things.

There are upscale nodes in the 'Image Trim & Concat Group', which you can un-bypass in order to active. This however results in HUGE images, so I've disabled them by default.

Stay Cheesy Y'all!~

Move the camera to a side view (profile) from the right so the full body of the character is visible. The character stands with both arms extended slightly downward and close to the thighs, keeping the body evenly balanced. Background is plain white. The character is facing the right.
